AB  - Background: Bipolar disorder is a potentially lifelong and disable condition. It is of ten comorbid with other psychiatric disorders and causes substantial psychosocial morbidity. Even during periods of euthymia, patients may experience impairments in psychosocial functioning [1]. Poor treatment compliance is one of the main challenges to control the symptoms and prevent relapsing episodes. The insight, the disease awareness and the patient's attitude towards medication are believed to affect the adherence to treatment [2]. Although the evidence of specific psychosocial interventions for bipolar disorder is slowly building, there are studies showing positive effects of psychoeducation on enhancing bipolar patients' medication adherence [3]. However, in psycho logical treatment trials the recruited participants are usually euthymic, with no comorbidity and had moderate levels of bipolar disorder. Therefore, samples of ten exclude many of the individuals comprising the largest proportion of clinical caseload and are not representative of the cases that are most difficult to manage. The aim of this study is to assess the impact of psycho-educational group program on the attitude towards medication and global functioning of real patients with bipolar disorder. Method(s): We performed a non-randomized controlled trial, pre-post intervention study. We obtain a sample of 14 patients being attended in a public community mental health center who had being diagnosed of bipolar disease type I or type II based on a psychiatric structured interview. All subjects were assessed at baseline, one month and three months after the end of the psychoeducative program using Drug Attitude Inventory (DAI) and Functioning Assessment Short Test (FAST). We based our program in the shortened version of the Psychoeducation Manual for Bipolar Disorder [4] composed of 8 weekly sessions of 90 minutes, each aimed at improving illness awareness, treatment compliance, early detection of prodromal symptoms and recur rences and life-style regularity. Socio-demographic data and clinical variables were also recorded. Result(s): The study results are preliminary so far and contain data from the one-month-assessment. Mean age was 46.9 (SD 13.6), 64.3% were female, 42.7% have psychiatric comorbidity and 64.3% substance abuse. Mean number of hospitalizations: 2.5 (SD 3.3). Clinical Global Impressions Scale for use in Bipolar Disorder (CGI-BP) at baseline (mean 2.86; SD 1.7). Although the mean is slightly higher in one month assessment DAI (mean 16.9; SD 2.8) compare to the baseline test (mean 15.6;SD 2.9), it does not pass significant levels (P = 0.076). FAST mean score before (mean26.8;SD 15) and afterthe intervention (mean 31.5;SD 15.8) has not revealed any significant differences (P = 0.72). Conclusion(s): Our preliminary results do not support previous evidence of the effectiveness of psycho-educational therapies for improving medications adherence and global functioning in bipolar patients. However, we are aware that limitations of the study may affect the results. The small sample size and the severity of bipolar disorder among patients may act as biases and confounding factors difficult to control in clinical practice. Nonetheless, we have expectations of this study to be continued over time and we are hopeful that with a larger number of patients the results may become statistical significant.
