AB  - This study is a process-oriented program evaluation of the Critical Time Intervention (CTI) (Susser, Valencia, Conover, Felix, Tsai, & Wyatt 1997), an approach to prevent recurrent homelessness in a group of mentally ill men. CTI was designed to prevent homelessness by improving the continuity of care for individuals being discharged from institutional to community living (CTI group n = 48, control group n = 48). CTI workers provided services based on both clinical judgment and clients' assessments of their service needs. Although many interventions with this group fail because of disagreements between clients and service providers, CTI bridges this gap by allowing a collaborative alliance between the two. The results of this controlled study showed that CTI was effective in reducing homeless nights. However, although this major outcome assessment was completed, it was still not clear what about the program was effective with which clients under what circumstances (Paul, 1967). The specific aims of this study are to examine several other process and outcome variables of the CTI intervention, such as type and frequency of services accessed by men in the CTI group, the types of housing CTI clients gravitated to, and their quality of life ratings as compared to men in the control group. The relationship between schizophrenic symptomatology and nights homeless is explored, and substance abuse is examined as a possible modifier of CTI's effect. Qualitative narratives by CTI workers about the course of intervention for each of the subjects in the CTI group are also reviewed to understand the mechanisms through which CTI operated. Results revealed that there were no differences in patterns of service utilization between the CTI and control groups. Subjects accessed medical, mental health, and substance abuse services at roughly the same rates. Nor were there significant differences in the use of psychiatric emergency room visits, or medical emergency room visits. Men in both CTI and control groups stayed in the same types of housing for roughly equal amounts of time, and rates of hospitalization and jail time were similar. Finally, there were no differences in quality of life ratings or satisfaction with current housing ratings. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)
