AB  - An attempt was made to assess the effectiveness of marital therapy on drinking behavior. After hospitalization for treatment of alcoholism, 40 alcoholics (5 F's), & their spouses, volunteered for marital group therapy on an outpatient basis; 20 couples participated while 20 were placed on a waiting list. Emphasis in therapy was placed on problem-solving techniques. The groups did not differ with respect to age, occupation, mean number of prior hospitalizations for alcoholism, or in mean scores on the Primary Communication Inventory or the Conjugal Life questionnaire (both from A. Ely, "Efficacy of Training in Confugal Therapy," Rutgers U, 1970). At 6-month follow-up, 9 of the therapy group & 2 of the waiting-list group were abstinent. The spouses of the drinking patients who were in therapy had significantly lower scores on the Conjugal Life questionnaire than the spouses of abstinent patients in therapy, indicating that they had more difficulty with acceptance & trust. Relapses tended to occur within the first 3 months following hospital discharge; those patients in therapy & abstinent at 3 months were also abstinent at 6 months. Case histories are presented to illustrate which type of alcoholics benefit from marital group therapy. The findings suggest that marital group therapy is an effective form of important follow-up treatment. 1 Table. Modified HA.
