AB  - Objectives: Use of patient‐centered approaches that utilize principles of shared decision making have been shown to improve the quality of health care decisions and outcomes. Despite demonstrated effectiveness, family involvement in the mental health care of individuals with serious mental illness (SMI) has been minimal. A mismatch in consumer and family preferences for involvement and clinical offering may drive this gap. We tested an innovative, preference‐driven manualized program to increase recovery of individuals with SMI and to engage and their families in care. Methods: A total of 232 Veterans with a psychotic disorder were randomly assigned to the patient centered approach, Family Member Provider Outreach (FMPO), or to enhanced treatment as usual at 2 VA medical centers. Participants completed baseline and 6‐month follow up interviews. FMPO consisted of up to 3 sessions with the Veteran and then up to 3 sessions with the family. Results: Patients were 51.6 years old (SD=9.1) and had 13 years of education (SD=2). The majority were male (84%), and 45% lived with family members. 70% of Veteran wanted their family to be able to contact the treatment team, 61% wanted their family to receive educational materials, 54% wanted their family to attend an educational or support group, and 50% wanted their family to attend a conjoint treatment session. 85% (92/108) of Veterans participated in at least one FMPO session (mean session number 1.80 (SD=.36); mode 2). Of the Veterans who had a session 54/92 (59%) had at least one family FMPO session (mean session number 2.24 (SD=.12); mode 3). Between groups comparisons revealed that individuals in FMPO had an improved measure of recovery (p<.05) and reduced paranoid ideation (p<.01). Conclusions: The study findings suggest that the majority of consumers want their family involved, but demonstrate a wide range of preferences. Engagement with the Veteran, using a shared decision making process and motivational interviewing, produced family engagement in FMPO. Further, this approach was able to improve an indicator of recovery and reduce symptoms. The study contributes to an emerging body of research suggesting that patient centered approaches can improve quality and outcomes of care.
