AB  - Objective: Severe mental disorders (SMD), as Schizophrenia and Bipolar Disorder, affects approximately 2.5-3% of the general adult population (OMS 2000). They are characterised by clinical severity, disability and dependency (Slade et al. 1997), higher morbidity and mortality (Newcomer et al. 2007). Psychosocial interventions improve SMD outcome but the fragmentation of mental health services is a handicap for the continuity of the treatment. Thus our objective is to evaluate the effectiveness of an Integrated Care Program for SMD, that should ensure a better outcome for these patients and their families and an improvement in the use of health system budgets. Method(s): 40 outpatients from Area 5 in Valencia (Spain), with Schizophrenia, Bipolar Disorder or Schizoaffective disorder diagnosis (DSM IV-TR) were randomly included in a control or an intervention group. Age range comprised 19-58 years old (Mean age = 38.21) and GAF\45. The 20 subjects intervention group consisted on an individualised care program (group or individual CBT, family therapy and psychoeducation on healthy habits, social or practitioner intervention). Coordination between care givers (psychiatrists, psychologists, nurses, social worker and practitioners) and follow up of the patient were permanent, ensuring the program fulfilling and detecting any adverse event. Clinical, functional and physical evaluations were performed to every subject and their families before the intervention, after it and 3 months later. chi2, T-tests and correlation analysis were performed. Result(s): Intervention group showed a clinical and functional significant improvement in comparison to the control group (P<0.05). Family coping strategies improved in the intervention group (P<0.05). Intervention group subjects and families expressed more satisfaction with the mental health service. Conclusion(s): Thus the effectiveness of the Intervention Care program was demonstrated. Policy of full disclosure: Financial help