AB  - Personal construct theory (PCP) may provide a way for people who are violent and have schizophrenia to understand and modify their behavior. The ability to reconstrue personal relationships may lead to greater acceptance of perceived or real stresses and increased tolerance. A year-long pilot study tested the feasibility of PCP- oriented psychotherapy among long-term male residents with schizophrenia in a hospital for mentally ill offenders, all of whom had committed violent acts. A matched group completed the same instruments, but did not receive group psychotherapy. Six of the 8 Ss from the index group completed the therapy, but instrument compliance varied. An individual case report is offered, demonstrating the changes in construing that occurred over the year. These included elaboration accompanied by changes in mood, and the formation of a more appropriate construct system for managing personal relationships. The model for therapy is feasible within a secure environment, although there are ethical issues. The evaluation of outcome requires substantial modification, and the issue of S cooperation needs further attention. The pilot does, however, suggest that such work is then worth more substantial study, including randomization between treatment and non-treatment groups. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2019 APA, all rights reserved)
