AB  - There is substantial room for improvement in the outcomes of youth substance use treatment. Interventions that simultaneously target risk factors and build protective factors for youth substance use may improve outcomes. This cohort-controlled trial examined whether the Grit strengths-based self-regulation group program, enhanced the substance use, mental ill-health and wellbeing outcomes of young people accessing residential treatment for substance use disorders. Participants were 251 young people (18-35 years) accessing two residential rehabilitation services in Queensland, Australia. Participants received either 6-weeks of standard treatment, or standard treatment + Grit (2 sessions each week for 6 weeks). Grit uses a strengths-based focuses on improving substance use, mental ill-health and wellbeing outcomes by building self-regulation skills and social connections. Participants substance use, depression/anxiety and wellbeing outcomes were assessed at baseline, 6 weeks, 3, 6 and 2 months post-program enrolment. There were 251 (64% male, Mage = 27.36) young people included in the study. The main drug of concern was methamphetamine (47.6%) followed by alcohol (27.1%). Comorbid mental health concerns were high. Preliminary results revealed that both groups showed a significant improvement in wellbeing and depressive symptoms, and decreases in alcohol use and methamphetamine use at 3 months. The Grit group showed greater reductions in tobacco use, and fewer problems associated with their methamphetamine use at the 3 month follow-up. These preliminary results suggest that the Grit program resulted in reductions in methamphetamine and tobacco use concerns, over and above the effects of the standard 6-week residential treatment program. The 6-week program itself, which is brief in comparison to other residential programs, resulted in reductions in substance use and improvements in wellbeing and depression at 3 months. The 6 and 12 month outcomes of the trial will be presented. Targeting protective factors as well as the underlying risk factors for substance use, not just substance use, may improve the outcomes of youth residential treatment.
