AB  - Background: People with schizophrenia have significant difficulties with cognition and social skills that negatively impact community functioning. Recovery oriented programs offer skills training to overcome these deficits, but problems generalizing what is learned, coupled with self defeating beliefs, environmental factors and motivational impairment often hamper the translation of the learned skills to community functioning. We developed a program of community based skills coaching (CBC) to provide an opportunity to practice the skills learned in the clinic, in relevant community situations. Methods: Four MA level clinicians were trained to provide CBC. The coaches helped their clients practice identified deficient skills (eg social, travel, independent living) an average of 2 hrs/week. We examined the functional abilities of all individuals diagnosed with schizophrenia or schizoaffective disorder, aged 18‐ 58, who were enrolled for at least 4 months during 2012 in a recovery clinic and receiving group based skills training (cognitive remediation, CBT, DBT) to address neuro and social cognition, psychotic symptoms, social and motivational deficits. Ten individuals identified at intake as having the most difficulty with community functioning were offered CBC in addition to the clinic based group program; another 10 individuals participated only in clinic based groups. The clinic routinely administers the Multnomah Community Ability Scale (MCAS) upon intake and 4 months later by 3 individual care coordinators, trained to rate with good inter‐rater reliability (.87). Results: CBC recipients had significantly lower MCAS scores at Time 1 (p <.002) indicating worse community functioning at intake than the individuals who received clinic based treatment . The MCAS scores of the CBC participants increased significantly from Time 1 (M = 60, SD = 8.43) to Time 2 (M = 65.60, SD = 6.72) whereas the MCAS scores of those receiving clinic based training did not change significantly: Time 1 (M = 72, SD = 6.63); Time 2 (M = 70.40, SD = 6.20). CBC participants showed significantly more improvement in their functional skills than those receiving only clinic based treatment (p <.004). Conclusion: It is feasible to provide community based skills training to participants in recovery oriented programs and this form of treatment may facilitate faster functional improvement than is seen when all treatment is clinic based. Further research with a randomized controlled trial, using blinded raters, is indicated.
