AB  - Background: The high prevalence of relapse following substance use disorder (SUD) treatment highlights the need for improved aftercare interventions. Mindfulness-Based Relapse Prevention (MBRP) is a group-based psychosocial aftercare program for individuals with substance use disorders. MBRP integrates evidence-based relapse prevention (RP) strategies with mindfulness-based interventions and aims to foster increased awareness of triggers, cravings, and habitual reactions and reduce relapse risk. In previous studies, MBRP resulted in lower levels of craving compared to treatment as usual (TAU; Bowen et al., 2009) and was more effective in preventing substance use and heavy drinking relapse at 12-month follow-up compared to both TAU and RP (Bowen et al., 2014). While initial results are promising, there is a paucity of MBRP efficacy studies, none of which have examined MBRP programs adapted for Veteran populations. Therefore, the present study aims to: 1) establish the feasibility of enrolling and retaining Veterans in an adapted 8-week MBRP protocol for Veterans in outpatient aftercare treatment at the San Francisco Veterans Affairs Healthcare System, and 2) obtain preliminary assessment of the efficacy of this program to increase mindfulness and reduce the risk for relapse. Method(s): Veterans in outpatient aftercare treatment for substance use disorders were eligible to participate and were assessed at baseline and post-MBRP. We tallied the number of Veterans referred vs. enrolled, the percent of visits attended, and percent of MBRP completers as defined by attendance of the Week-8 session. Random-intercept linear mixed models were used to explore the efficacy of MBRP on increasing trait mindfulness and reducing the risk for relapse. Trait mindfulness was assessed using the Freiburg Mindfulness Inventory (FMI), which is a valid and reliable self-report questionnaire for measuring mindfulness (Walach et al., 2006). Relapse risk was assessed using the Brief Addiction Monitor (BAM), which is a valid and reliable self-report measure assessing substance use, relapse risk and protective factors (Cacciola et al., 2013). Result(s): 54 Veterans were referred and 18 (33.3%; 2 female) between the ages of 34 and 73 enrolled in the program. Out of 144 possible visits (8 sessions*18 participants), 86% of the sessions were attended. 15 participants (83.3%) completed the adapted MBRP program. Trait mindfulness significantly increased following treatment (F(1,14)=5.12, p=0.04). Although not statistically significant, results also indicated a numerical reduction in substance-related risk factors and an increase in protective factors following MBRP. Three participants (17%) reported active substance use at baseline; all of whom reported abstinence at follow-up. Conclusion(s): These preliminary findings suggest that enrollment and retention of Veterans in an adapted version of MBRP is feasible and may be effective for increasing mindfulness and reducing relapse risk. Summary: The integration of evidence-based relapse prevention strategies and targeted mindfulness interventions may contribute to an increased ability to identify and adaptively cope with distress associated with craving and negative affect for Veterans in outpatient aftercare treatment for substance use disorders. Further study of this program is warranted.
