AB  - Background: In connection with the National Mental Health Policy published in 2006, the Ministry of Health of Turkey began to put more focus on community-based mental health services. Accordingly, starting from 2009, Community Mental Health Centers (CMHC) have been established in many regions and districts of the country. Thus, in addition to institutionbased care already provided by outpatient and inpatient clinics in mental health hospitals and psychiatry departments of general hospitals, a community-based mental health care system is targeted [1]. CMHCs provide a comprehensive mental health service including psychoeducation, rehabilitation and home visits as well as the treatment and follow-up of psychiatric patients. In the literature, favourable outcomes of deinstitutionalisation have been mentioned, in the presence of adequate community support systems [2]. Thornicroft and Tansella emphasized a balanced approach integrating both inpatient and community mental health care [3]. Aim(s): The aim of our study was to investigate the effect of CMHC services on clinical parameters in psychotic patients. Method(s): All patients registered to Bakirkoy CMHC in 2012, having a diagnosis of psychotic disorder (including schizophrenia, schizoaffective disorder and psychotic disorder not otherwise specified) and at least 5 years of illness were included in the study. Along with sociodemographic data, clinical parameters such as compliance to treatment, relapses, hospitalizations, suicidal and homicidal behaviors and functionality were investigated in a 2-year period before application to CMHC and a 2-year period of follow-up in CMHC and compared. Result(s): In a total number of 54 patients, 29 (54%) were female, 25 (46%) were male and the mean age was 49.5+/-14.8 (range: 24-79) years. The majority was single (n = 34, 63%) and unemployed (n = 45, 83%). 45 (83%) patients received individual counseling, 17 (32%) participated in group therapy and 24 (44%) in rehabilitation during this 2-year period of follow-up. Home visits were made in 33 (61%) patients. When 2-year periods before and in CMHC were compared, there was a significant difference in the rates of relapses, hospitalizations, suicidal and homicidal behaviors, compliance to treatment, depressive symptoms and insight. No significant difference was obtained in occupational functionality. Conclusion(s): The main target population of community-based mental health model consists of patients with severe mental disorders [1]. The majority of patients seen by community mental health teams has been reported to have psychotic disorders in the study of Keown et al. [4]. According to the findings of our study, treatment and follow-up of psychotic patients in CMHCs may have a positive effect on many clinical parameters. When psychiatric disorders considered as an important public health problem, community-based mental health approach may have an essential role in the solution. In order to accomplish a more comprehensive mental health service, establishment of half-way houses, sheltered homes and sheltered workplaces should also be considered.
