AB  - The state of Oklahoma has the highest rate of incarceration of women in the United States, with almost twice the national average (Oklahoma Department of Corrections, 2011). Studies with incarcerated women have shown high rates of trauma exposure and substance use compared to community populations. The Oklahoma Department of Corrections (DOC) has implemented treatment programs to address these complex problems in incarcerated women. Helping Women Recover/Beyond Trauma (HWR/BT; Covington, 2003, 2008) is a manualized group treatment which addresses trauma and substance use in an integrated format specific to women. The purpose of the present study was to evaluate the effectiveness of this comprehensive HWR/BT-based treatment program versus a matched comparison sample not attending the target treatment. Self-report measures were collected during the week before and after the 4-month treatment, and included assessments of posttraumatic stress, substance use self-efficacy, and other mental health symptoms. Baseline data was collected from 95 women, with 56 women in the final completer sample. Results indicated statistically significant pre-post and between-group differences, favoring the treatment group, for negative posttraumatic cognitions. Pre-post, but not between-group, improvements were also observed for PTSD and substance-related self-efficacy. Results indicate preliminary effectiveness for this integrated treatment program for reducing trauma- and substance-related symptoms in incarcerated women. More research is needed regarding mental health symptoms. Further investigation is also needed regarding the unique benefit of the treatment over standard prison services. Implications and future directions are discussed. Copies of dissertations may be obtained by addressing your request to ProQuest, 789 E. Eisenhower Parkway, P.O. Box 1346, Ann Arbor, MI 48106-1346. Telephone 1-800-521-3042; e-mail: disspub@umi.com
