AB  - Assessed the safety and efficacy of venlafaxine for the treatment of attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) in 10 adults (mean age 34.5 yrs) with comorbid alcohol use disorders and cocaine abuse. The effects of venlafaxine treatment on alcohol craving and alcohol use was also assessed. Ss were seen weekly for the supportive psychotherapy and medication monitoring during weeks 1, 2, 3, 4, 8, and 12. Alcohol or cocaine/dependence was determined by using the substance-abuse module of the Structured Clinical Interview for Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders-III-Revised (DSM-III-R). Ss were allowed to participate in Alcoholics Anonymous and routine outpatient group and/or individual therapy for alcohol abuse/dependence. All but 1 S had significant decreases in substance use during the follow-up period, and 3 reported complete abstinence. The results of this preliminary study suggest that venlafaxine may be effective treatment for ADHD in adults with comorbid alcohol use disorders and may decrease alcohol craving frequency and intensity. The effect of cocaine use, if any, was difficult to interpret in this trial. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2018 APA, all rights reserved)
